{"title_page": "2014 Brazilian general election", "text_new": "{{short description|Election for President, Congress, and state positions in Brazil in 2014}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2014 Brazilian presidential election\n| country = Brazil\n| flag_year = 2014\n| type = Presidential\n| vote_type = Popular \n| ongoing = no\n| alliance_name     = Testing\n<!--- Dilma Rousseff --->\n| previous_election  = 2010 Brazilian presidential election\n| previous_year = 2010\n| election_date  = 5 October 2014 (first round)<br />26 October 2014 (second round)\n| next_election = 2018 Brazilian general election\n| next_year = 2018\n| turnout = 78.90%\n| image1 = [[File:Dilma Rousseff 2011.jpg|200x200px]]\n| nominee1 = [[Dilma Rousseff]]\n| party1 = Workers' Party (Brazil)\n| alliance1 = {{nowrap|[[With the Strength of the People]]}}\n| home_state1 = [[Minas Gerais]]\n| running_mate1 = [[Michel Temer]]\n| states_carried1    = '''15'''\n<!--- A\u00e9cio Neves --->\n| popular_vote1 = '''54,501,119'''\n| percentage1 = '''51.64%'''\n| map_image = 2014 Brazilian presidential election map (Round 2).svg\n| map_size = 400px\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Dilma Rousseff]]\n| before_party = Workers' Party (Brazil)\n| after_election = [[Dilma Rousseff]]\n| after_party  = Workers' Party (Brazil)\n| nominee2 = [[A\u00e9cio Neves]]\n| image2 = [[File:A\u00e9cio Neves em 23 de outubro de 2014-2.jpg|200x200px]]\n| party2 = Brazilian Social Democracy Party\n| alliance2 =  [[Brazil can do more|Change Brazil]]\n| home_state2 = [[Minas Gerais]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Aloysio Nunes]]\n| popular_vote2 = 51,041,155\n| percentage2 = 48.36%\n| states_carried2    = 11+[[Brazilian Federal District|DF]]\n<!--- Map --->\n}}\n\n'''General elections''' were held in [[Brazil]] on 5 October 2014 to elect the [[President of Brazil|President]], the [[National Congress of Brazil|National Congress]], [[2014 Brazilian gubernatorial elections|state governors]] and state legislatures.<ref name=\"Terra\">[http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/politica/tse-aprova-calendario-e-divulga-datas-das-eleicoes-de-2014,37d5c160a9ace310VgnVCM10000098cceb0aRCRD.html \"TSE aprova calend\u00e1rio e divulga datas das elei\u00e7\u00f5es de 2014\"]. [[Terra Networks|Terra]]. 22 May 2013. Retrieved 2 December 2013.</ref> As no candidate in the presidential and several gubernatorial elections received more than 50% of the vote, a second-round [[Two-round system|runoff]] was held on 26 October.<ref name=\"Terra\" />\n\nIn the first round of voting [[Dilma Rousseff]] won 41.6% of the vote, ahead of [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] with 33.6% and [[Marina Silva]] with 21.3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2014 \u2013 Resultados das Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2014 para Presidente|url=http://www.eleicoes2014.com.br}}</ref> Rousseff and Neves contested the runoff on 26 October and Rousseff won re-election by a narrow margin, 51.6% to Neves' 48.4%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-29782073|title=Dilma Rousseff re-elected Brazilian president|date=26 October 2014|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Presidential election==\nIncumbent President [[Dilma Rousseff]] of the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Workers' Party]] (PT), Brazil's first female president, was challenged by 11 other candidates. [[Minas Gerais]] [[Senate of Brazil|Senator]] [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] from the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party]] (PSDB) and [[Marina Silva]] from the [[Brazilian Socialist Party]] (PSB) were her main rivals. Since none of the candidates obtained over 50% of the valid votes in the 5 October election, a [[two-round system|second-round]] election was held on 26 October between Rousseff and Neves, who had finished first and second respectively in the 5 October vote.\n\nIn Brazil's closest presidential election results since 1989, Rousseff narrowly defeated Neves in the second round, taking 51.6% of the vote to Neves' 48.4%.\n\nThe original PSB candidate had been [[Eduardo Campos]]. However, he died in a [[2014 Santos Cessna Citation accident|plane crash]] in [[Santos, S\u00e3o Paulo|Santos]] on 13 August 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/08/1499718-presidenciavel-eduardo-campos-morre-em-acidente-aereo-em-santos-sp.shtml|title=Presidenci\u00e1vel Eduardo Campos morre em acidente a\u00e9reo em Santos (SP) - 13/08/2014 - Poder - Folha de S.Paulo|publisher=|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> after which the party chose Silva, who had been his running mate, to replace him as the presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-28822676|title=Brazil: Marina Silva 'to replace' late candidate Campos|date=16 August 2014|publisher=|accessdate=22 November 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaign Issues ===\n\n==== Economy ====\n\n===== Dilma Rousseff =====\n\nDefended the significant economic gains and improvements in living standards of her own administration and that of her predecessor, Lula da Silva.\n\n===== A\u00e9cio Neves =====\nProposed sweeping reductions in the welfare state and state intervention in the economy.\n\n==== Allegations of corruption ====\nShortly before the election a former executive of the state-run oil company [[Petrobras]] accused a minister, three state governors, six senators and dozens of congressmen from President Dilma Rousseff's Workers\u2019 Party (PT) and several coalition allies of having accepted [[kickback (bribery)|kickback]]s from contracts.<ref>\n{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/09/scandal-brazil\n|title=The Petrobras affair\n|newspaper=The Economist|\nissn=0013-0613\n|access-date=2016-05-07\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Candidates===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|#\n!colspan=2|Presidential candidate\n!colspan=2|Vice-Presidential candidate\n!Party/coalition\n|-\n| style=\"background:#DA1208;\"|\n| 13\n| [[File:Dilma Rousseff - foto oficial 2011-01-09.jpg|110px]]\n| [[Dilma Rousseff]] (PT)\n| [[File:Michel Temer (foto 2).jpg|110px]]\n| [[Michel Temer]] (PMDB)\n| <center>''[[With the Strength of the People]]''<br /><small>[[Workers' Party (Brazil)|PT]], [[Brazilian Democratic Movement|PMDB]], [[Social Democratic Party (Brazil, 2011)|PSD]], [[Progressistas|PP]], [[Liberal Party (Brazil, 2006)|PR]], [[Democratic Labor Party (Brazil)|PDT]], [[Republicanos|PRB]], [[Republican Party of the Social Order|PROS]], [[Communist Party of Brazil|PCdoB]]</small></center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FF0000;\"|\n| 16\n| [[File:(2015-06-04) 2\u00ba Congresso Nacional da CSP-Conlutas Dia1 152 Romerito Pontes (18687750336).jpg|110px]]\n| [[Jos\u00e9 Maria de Almeida]] (PSTU)\n| <!-- Do not place a placeholder image here, per WP:IPH -->\n| Cl\u00e1udia Durans (PSTU)\n| <center>[[Unified Workers' Socialist Party]] (PSTU)</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#009038;\"|\n| 20\n| [[File:Pastor everaldo abr (edited).jpeg|110px]]\n| [[Everaldo Pereira]] (PSC)\n| <!-- Do not place a placeholder image here, per WP:IPH -->\n| Leonardo Gadelha (PSC)\n| <center>[[Social Christian Party (Brazil)|Social Christian Party]] (PSC)</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#DA251C;\"|\n| 21\n| [[File:Mauro Iasi no Senado.png|110px]]\n| Mauro Iasi (PCB)\n| <!-- Do not place a placeholder image here, per WP:IPH -->\n| Sofia Manzano (PCB)\n| <center>[[Brazilian Communist Party]] (PCB)</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#254890;\"|\n| 27\n| [[File:Jos\u00e9 Maria Eymael (4764807212).jpg|110px]]\n| [[Jos\u00e9 Maria Eymael]] (PSDC)\n| <!-- Do not place a placeholder image here, per WP:IPH -->\n| Roberto Lopes (PSDC)\n| <center>[[Christian Democracy (Brazil)|Social Democratic Christian Party]] (PSDC)</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#2CB53F;\"|\n| 28\n|\n| [[Levy Fidelix]] (PRTB)\n| <!-- Do not place a placeholder image here, per WP:IPH -->\n| Jos\u00e9 Alves de Oliveira (PRTB)\n| <center>[[Brazilian Labour Renewal Party]] (PRTB)</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#9F030A;\"|\n| 29\n| [[File:Rui Costa Pimenta PCO ABr.jpg|110px]]\n| Rui Costa Pimenta (PCO)\n| <!-- Do not place a placeholder image here, per WP:IPH -->\n| Ricardo Machado (PCO)\n| <center>[[Labour Cause's Party]] (PCO)</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FF6600;\"|\n| 40\n| [[File:MarinaSilva2010.jpg|110px]]\n| [[Marina Silva]] (PSB)\n| [[File:Beto Albuquerque.jpg|110px]]\n| Beto Albuquerque (PSB)\n| <center>''United for Brazil''<br /><small>[[Brazilian Socialist Party|PSB]], [[Cidadania|PPS]], [[Social Liberal Party (Brazil)|PSL]], [[Humanist Party of Solidarity|PHS]], [[Free Fatherland Party (Brazil)|PPL]], [[Republican Progressive Party (Brazil)|PRP]]</small></center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#006600;\"|\n| 43\n| [[File:Eduardojorge pv abr.jpg|110px]]\n| [[Eduardo Jorge]] (PV)\n| [[File:C\u00e9lia Sacramento.jpg|110px]]\n| C\u00e9lia Sacramento (PV)\n| <center>[[Green Party (Brazil)|Green Party]] (PV)</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#1E90FF;\"|\n| 45\n| [[File:A\u00e9cio Neves em 23 de outubro de 2014-2.jpg|110px]]\n| [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] (PSDB)\n| [[File:Aloysio nunes 2011.jpg|110px]]\n| [[Aloysio Nunes]] (PSDB)\n| <center>''[[Change Brazil]]''<br /><small>[[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]], [[Solidariedade|SD]], [[Party of National Mobilization|PMN]], [[Patriota|PEN]], [[Podemos (Brazil)|PTN]], [[Christian Labour Party|PTC]], [[Democrats (Brazil)|DEM]], [[Avante (political party)|PTdoB]], [[Brazilian Labor Party (current)|PTB]]</small></center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ED040E;\"|\n| 50\n| [[File:Luciana genro 2007.jpg|110px]]\n| [[Luciana Genro]] (PSOL)\n| [[File:Jorge Paz em 2014.jpg|110px]]\n| Jorge Paz (PSOL)\n| <center>[[Socialism and Liberty Party]] (PSOL)</center>\n|}\n\n===Debates===\n===First round===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Host\n! Moderator\n! width=30| Dilma Rousseff (PT)\n! width=30| A\u00e9cio Neves (PSDB)\n! width=30| Marina Silva (PSB)\n! width=30| Luciana Genro (PSOL)\n! width=30| Eduardo Jorge (PV)\n! width=30| Everaldo Pereira (PSC)\n! width=30| Levy Fidelix (PRTB)\n! width=30| Jos\u00e9 Maria Eymael (PSDC)\n! width=30| Z\u00e9 Maria (PSTU)\n! width=30| Mauro Iasi (PCB)\n! width=30| Rui Costa Pimenta (PCO)\n|-\n| 26 August 2014\n| [[Rede Bandeirantes]]\n| [[Ricardo Boechat]]\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n|-\n| 1 September 2014\n| [[Sistema Brasileiro de Televis\u00e3o|SBT]], [[Folha de S.Paulo|Folha]], [[Jovem Pan]], [[Universo Online|UOL]]\n| Carlos Nascimento\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n|-\n| 16 September 2014\n| [[Rede Aparecida|TV Aparecida]], [[Episcopal Conference of Brazil|CNBB]]\n| Rodolpho Gamberini\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n|-\n| 28 September 2014\n| [[RecordTV|Rede Record]], R7\n| Celso Freitas, Adriana Ara\u00fajo\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n|-\n| 2 October 2014\n| [[Rede Globo]], [[G1 (website)|G1]]\n| [[William Bonner (newscaster)|William Bonner]]\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{ya|text=Present}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}\n| {{na|text=Not Invited}}