ginous; the claws of the tarsi ferruginous; wings fusco-hyaline, with a darker cloud beyond the enclosed cells, and adorned with a bright purple and coppery iridescence.  Length ten to eleven lines.\n''Hab.''&mdash;Sunda Islands.<ref name=\"Smith1874\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Distribution==\nAccording to entomologist Paul D. Hurd Jr., it is unknown when and how ''X. sonorina'' managed to reach the Hawaiian Islands.  Located in the [[Pacific Ocean]], more than {{convert|2000|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} away from the closest landfall in North America, Hawaii's great distance from the Americas is thought to have been too large for natural [[biological dispersal]] to succeed.  Hurd suggests that it is likely humans aided ''X. sonorina'' in its arrival to Hawaii.<ref name=\"Hurd1958\" />  Today, the species can be found on all of the main [[Hawaiian Islands]].<ref name=\"Scott-2000\" />  Following the colonization of Hawaii, ''X. sonorina'' was [[Adventive species|introduced]] into the Marianas Islands, China, Japan, and the United States.<ref name=\"Hurd1958\" />  The species has also been reported in [[Midway Atoll]], [[Java]], [[New Guinea]], and the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\"UH-IPMP\" />\n\nHurd observes that in recent history, only ''two'' species in the genus ''[[Xylocopa]]'' have successfully colonized Pacific archipelagos east of the Americas through natural biological dispersal or with human help; This is out of a total of more than 150 identified species in North and South America, 70 of which can be found in Brazil alone.  The two species include: ''Xylocopa darwinii'', found in the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]],  {{convert|604|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} west of [[South America]], with the mainland of [[Ecuador]] as the closest land mass; and ''Xylocopa clarionenis'', found on [[Clari\u00f3n Island]] in the [[Revillagigedo Islands]], {{convert|700|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} from the coast of Mexico.  ''X. clarionenis'' is thought to be most closely related to ''Xylocopa varipuncta''.<ref name=\"Hurd1958\" />\n\n==Life cycle==\nEntomologist Julian R. Yates III of the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] describes the life cycle of ''X. sonorina'' in Hawaii:\n<blockquote>Having located a suitable piece of wood, the female bee begins to excavate a single tunnel in preparation for egg laying. Because of our tropical climate, egg laying by female carpenter bees occurs year-round although it may decline during the winter months, when the weather is worse. Before laying eggs, the female collects pollen and deposits it, in the form of a ball, in the tunnel at a point furthest from the entrance. She lays a single egg on the pollen ball and seals both in a chamber with wood shavings. She may lay several eggs, each on its own pollen ball and inside its own sealed chamber, in a series within the tunnel. The eggs hatch in two to three days. The larvae develop in approximately two weeks. The prepupal (nonfeeding larvae) and pupal stages take about three to four weeks to reach adulthood. Teneral (adult shortly after emergence, when it is not entirely hardened or not of the mature color) females are fed by the mother. They are capable of buzzing in about a week, and of flight in approximately two to three weeks. A single female in a tunnel may be joined later by her offspring or other bees. Only one female will collect pollen, prepare cells, and lay eggs, however. Other females perform guard and nest-cleaning duties.<ref name=\"UH-IPMP\">{{cite web| last = Yates II| first = Julian R.| title = ''Xylocopa sonorina'' (Smith)| work = Urban Knowledge Master| publisher = University of Hawaii Integrated Pest Management Program| date = Dec 1992| url = http://www.extento.hawaii.edu/Kbase/urban/site/structural/Carpbee.htm | accessdate = 2009-05-04}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Behavior==\n[[File:Xylocopa wailea maui hawaii.jpg|thumb|''X. sonorina'' in a field of Chinese violet (''Asystasia gangetica'')]]\nThe foraging behavior of ''X. sonorina'' involves a quick series of movements between flowers.  In a 1996 study using ''[[Asystasia gangetica]]'' (Chinese violet), ''X. sonorina'' visited 16 flowers per minute and spent an average of 1.5 seconds at each flower, usually flying towards the flower from the front, landing on the petals, and moving to the bottom of the [[Petal#Corolla|corolla]].<ref name=\"Villalobos-1996\">{{cite journal| last = Villalobos| first = Ethel M.|author2=Todd E. Shelly | title = Temporal and spatial variation in the foraging behavior of honey bees (Hymenoptera: Apidae) at Chinese violets| journal = Florida Entomologist| volume = 79| issue = 3| pages = 398\u2013407| publisher = Florida Entomological Society| date = Sep 1996| url = http://www.fcla.edu/FlaEnt/fe79p398.pdf| doi=10.2307/3495589}}</ref> Another study found that ''X. sonorina'' was a primary and secondary nectar \"robber\" of ''A. gangetica'' since it \"took nectar through perforations and did not contact stigmas in doing so.\"<ref name=\"Barrows-1980\" /> Floral robbery occurs when the carpenter bee makes perforations near the base of the tubular corolla of the flower to obtain nectar, but does not pollinate the flower in return.<ref name=\"Barrows-1980\" />\n\nIn Hawaii and [[Niue Island]], ''X. sonorina'' has been used in [[tropical agriculture]] as a [[pollinator]] of ''[[Passiflora edulis]]'', a species of [[passion fruit]].<ref name=\"Donovan-1990\">{{cite journal| last = Donovan| first = B. J.| title = Selection and importation of new pollinators to New Zealand| journal = New Zealand Entomologist| volume = 13| issue = 1| pages = 26\u201332| publisher =  Entomological Society of New Zealand | year = 1990| url = http://www.ento.org.nz/nzentomologist/free_issues/NZEnto13_1_1990/Volume%2013-26-32.pdf| accessdate = 2009-05-05| doi=10.1080/00779962.1990.9722585}}</ref> Although valued for their pollination, carpenter bee nesting behavior often results in their classification as pests; The bees prefer to burrow into wood to create nest galleries.<ref name=\"Manson-1988\">{{cite journal| last = Manson| first = D. C. M.| title = The occurrence of the carpenter bee, ''Xylocopa sonorina'' in New Zealand| journal = The Weta| volume = 11| issue = 1| pages = 4\u20135| publisher =  Entomological Society of New Zealand | location =| year = 1988| url = http://www.ento.org.nz/nzentomologist/free_issues/Weta11_1_1988/Weta11(1)_4_5.pdf | accessdate = 2009-05-06}}</ref> Due to this problem, in 1934, a [[blister beetle]] (''[[Cissites auriculata]]'') was brought to Hawaii in an attempt to decrease the number of ''X. sonorina''; there is no evidence that ''C. auriculata'' became established.<ref name=\"Barrows-1980\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*\n*\n*\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|Xylocopa sonorina}}\n*Akamine et al. (1974). \"[http://hdl.handle.net/10125/15278 Passion fruit culture in Hawaii]\". ''Agricultural Economics Circular''; AEC-345. Honolulu (HI): University of Hawaii.\n*Gerling, Dan (1982). \"Nesting biology and flower relationships of Xylocopa sonorina Smith in Hawaii (Hymenoptera; Anthophoridae)\". Pan-Pacific Entomologist (Pacific Coast Entomological Society) 58 (4): 336\u2013351. {{issn|0031-0603}}.\n*Hurd, Jr., Paul (1955). \"[http://essig.berkeley.edu/documents/cis/cis04_2.pdf The Carpenter Bees of California (Hymenoptera: Apoidea)]\". ''Bulletin of the California Insect Survey''. Berkeley: University of California Press. '''4''' (2).{{Subscription required}}\n*Nishida, Toshiyuki (1963).  \"Ecology of the pollinators of passion fruit\".   Technical Bulletin.  Honolulu, HI: University of Hawaii, College of Tropical Agriculture, Hawaii Agricultural Experiment Station. 55: 1-38.\n*Perkins, R. C. L (1899). \"Hymenoptera Aculeata\". In David Sharp. ''[[Fauna Hawaiiensis|Fauna Hawaiiensis or the Zoology of the Sandwich (Hawaiian) Isles]]''. London: [[Cambridge University Press]]. pp.&nbsp;1\u2013115.\n*Tenorio, JoAnn M.; Gordon M. Nishida (1995). ''What's Bugging Me? Identifying and Controlling Household Pests in Hawai{{okina}}i.'' Honolulu, HI: [[University of Hawaii Press]]. pp.&nbsp;74\u201376. {{ISBN|0-8248-1742-7}}.\n*Timberlake, P. H. (1922). \"[http://hdl.handle.net/10125/15689 Identity of the Hawaiian carpenter bee of the genus Xylocopa (Hymenoptera)]\". ''[[Proceedings of the Hawaiian Entomological Society]]''. '''5''' (1): 51.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3482645}}\n\n[[Category:Xylocopa|sonorina]]\n[[Category:Hymenoptera of Oceania]]\n[[Category:Insects of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Insects of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Introduced animals of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Mariana Islands]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1874]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Northern Mariana Islands]]\n", "name_user": "Dyanega", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution:Hurd very explicitly states that these introductions all failed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xylocopa_sonorina"}
